snippet.textDisplay: So an opportunity popped up with a really good find, so I went and bought it for $500!!! This really shows you what you can do to find your first project car, find a budget suv, etc with minimal risk and a lot of potential reward!!! We used all common hand tools and did this job at home ourselves! Craftsman was bought by Stanley and now they have decent tools for the price! Worth taking a look at for sure! I messed with the 150 piece set for the first time and I liked it. It got the job done and I think you guys looking for your first set would find it to be a good starter set! Here is the link to the tool sets: http://bit.ly/2PNfHLS

snippet.textDisplay:
Changed my windshield washer reservoir on a 2004 Tacoma using only common hand tools... Had Chris fix influence at multiple points during the job...

1. Made sure I researched the part via owners manual to see if I had a low level sensor bc some 1st Gen Tacoma’s have it and some do not. Then compared the new part with the old part on scene.

2. Turned the wheels outward to work with the vehicle bc I couldn’t take the wheel off (don’t have a jack yet).

3. Put jack stands under the frame in case a opposite of a miracle happened and the truck collapsed while I was underneath it.

4. Put the reservoir on buckets while taking off the fluid line and electrical components, instead of letting it suspend in mid air.

5. Cleaned all parts that needed to be reused including the bolts with Soapy Wooder.

6. Looked into to buying medium strength thread locker while at the auto store. Ended up not using the locker bc it said to not use on plastic?

All of these hours of Chris Fix videos I’ve watched have become a valuable investment.

snippet.textDisplay:
Craftsman is definitely worth it. I bought a lithium ion cordless drill years ago and the thing has served me well since. I lost the charger more than a year ago and it's still working. At first I just bought what I could afford, but now I am happy because I got more than enough bang for my buck. I still use a lot of Craftsman stuff and love it. The only thing I regret is a screwdriver set. They don't use hardened steel apparently. They Just use regular steel and anodize it to make it shiny.
I will never buy Milwaukee though. I'm not that gullible.

snippet.textDisplay: I got a free 86 CRX from craigslist  once.  They said it wouldn't start and they just wanted the damn thing out of their driveway.  Told them I couldn't come until after work to get it. They said they'd leave the title signed and in  the glove box.  Sure enough it was there and signed. Wouldn't start , but it seemed like it wanted to. So we towed it to the nearest gas station. Used all the change they left in it to toss a gallon off gas in it. Started right up. My buddy followed me home. Ran great, until we went off reading with it :D
